Horace gives a point to his praises of country life by putting them into the mouth of a money-lender notorious for his keenness in his trade. Cp. the saying attributed apparently to the same person, the ‘ fenerator Alf1us‚' by Columella (1. 7), ⁶ vel optima nomina non appel- lando fieri mala,’ ‘that the best debtors become bad ones if you let them alone?
